Modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(leaps)
library(GGally)
library(knitr)

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. The data is collected using random sampling hence findings can be generalised on larger population.

Because the dataset is based only on reviews via rotten tomatoes and Internet Movie Database (IMDB), it might be biased, because we are considering audience rating from only two sources.

Part 2: Research question

The research question here is to identy whether a subset of variables from the given movie dataset can be used to predict the critic score of a particular movie. Identifying the popularity with critics can provide useful information about what features have to be in a movie that would be critic approved.However in the movie industry,critic scores show quite a different picture from audience scores.This analysis can help decide whether critics opinions are valuable at all for a movie.

The distribution of critic score looks to be nearly normal

qplot(genre,audience_score,data=movies,geom = c("boxplot","jitter"),
      fill=genre, main= "Genre", xlab = "gene", ylab = "audience_score")+
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))

Critics usually do not like the Action and Adventure genre,along with Comedy.Sci-fi movies too have a large range of scores,tending to low.However,these are also affected by high variance in critic scores,meaning that critics have diverse opinions. Critics rate Drama,Documentary and Musical and Performing Arts movies more,although outliers are seen. We will now use actor1 through actor5 variables to visualize their effect on critic scores.Do the Oscar nominationa have an effect on critic d=due to personal liking/bias?Lets find out.

Part 5: Prediction

We will be predicting the critic score for the mystery movie Die Hard 2.The values for the predictors were obtained from the sources mentioned in the codebook: IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes; and from common sense.

genre <- "Mystery & Suspense"
imdb_rating <- 7.1
audience_score <- 70
director <- "Renny Harlin"
critics_score <- 69
TestA <- data.frame (genre, imdb_rating,audience_score,critics_score, director)
prediction_DH2 <- predict(m_comp,newdata=TestA, interval="confidence")
myPrediction <- round(predict(m_comp, TestA), digits = 0)
c(myPrediction, TestA$critics_score) #compare fitted and observed values
##  1    
## 65 69
prediction_DH2
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 65.10004 48.17126 82.02881

The predicted critic score is 65 which is close to the actual 69,and is contained in the 95% confidence interval

Part 6: Conclusion

Explanatory data analysis proved to be a valuable process in identifying what feature matters most to achieve better results. The model developed predicted the critic score for the movie. The first observation is that we have limited amount of data. Data from different geners equally distributed would help to train the model more accurately. Information such as gross estimated and actual earnings by movies is missing and could be helpful to have more insights for following critic feedback .
